eatment with orlistat. After two weeks of treatment, she reports changes in her bowel movements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most common stool-related side effect of this medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Constipation","Oily, loose stools","Bloody stools","Green-coloured stools","Hard, pellet-like stools"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOily, loose stools\u003C/strong\u003E (steatorrhoea) are the most common stool-related side effect of orlistat. This occurs because orlistat inhibits pancreatic lipase, preventing dietary fat absorption. The unabsorbed fat is then excreted in the faeces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect, and explained below: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstipation\u003C/strong\u003E: orlistat typically causes loose rather than constipated stools due to the presence of unabsorbed fats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBloody stools\u003C/strong\u003E: orlistat does not cause gastrointestinal bleeding. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreen-coloured stools\u003C/strong\u003E: while stool colour can vary, green is not a characteristic change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHard, pellet-like stools\u003C/strong\u003E: orlistat causes loose, oily stools rather than hard stools. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther common gastrointestinal side effects include flatulence, faecal urgency, and abdominal cramping. These effects are typically more pronounced when consuming meals high in fat.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Orlistat causes steatorrhoea (fatty stools) due to increased faecal fat excretion.","Gastrointestinal side effects are common with orlistat due to its mechanism of blocking fat absorption.","Unabsorbed dietary fats are excreted in the faeces, leading to oily, loose stools."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16775"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T17:17:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T17:18:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9466"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA